Here, the transient part of the equation is $2 \mathrm{e}^{\wedge}-\mathrm{t}$ because as t approaches to infinity, the term becomes 0 . Hence, $2 \mathrm{e}^{\wedge}$-t is the transient term. In the case of the first term 5 , it will remain same when $t$ approaches infinity. Hence, 5 is the steady-state term of the equation.

