\section*{Nyquist stability criteria}

The closed loop transfer function is given by:
$\mathrm{C}(\mathrm{s}) / \mathrm{R}(\mathrm{s})=\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}) /(1+\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}) \mathrm{H}(\mathrm{s}))$

Where,
$C(s)$ is the output of the given control system
$R(s)$ in the input of the given control system
$\mathrm{H}(\mathrm{s})$ is the feedback path
$G(s)$ is the forward path of a system

The characteristic equation of the system is given by the condition $1+\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}) \mathrm{H}(\mathrm{s})=0$.
We know that $\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}) \mathrm{H}(\mathrm{s})$ in terms of zeroes and poles is given by:
$G(s) H(s)=\frac{K\left(s+z_{1}\right)\left(s+z_{2}\right)\left(s+z_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+z_{m}\right)}{\left(s+p_{1}\right)\left(s+p_{2}\right)\left(s+p_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+p_{n}\right)}$

The value of $m$ is less or equal to $n$. It means that for an ideal control system, the number of zeroes is always less than or equal to the number of poles in a given control system.

Let, $\mathrm{F}(\mathrm{s})=1+\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}) \mathrm{H}(\mathrm{s})$

Putting the value of $\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}) \mathrm{H}(\mathrm{s})$ in the above equation, we get:
$$\begin{aligned}
& F(s)=\frac{K\left(s+z_{1}\right)\left(s+z_{2}\right)\left(s+z_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+z_{m}\right)}{\left(s+p_{1}\right)\left(s+p_{2}\right)\left(s+p_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+p_{n}\right)}+1 \\
& F(s)=\frac{\left(s+p_{1}\right)\left(s+p_{2}\right)\left(s+p_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+p_{n}\right)+K\left(s+z_{1}\right)\left(s+z_{2}\right)\left(s+z_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+z_{m}\right)}{\left(s+p_{1}\right)\left(s+p_{2}\right)\left(s+p_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+p_{n}\right)} \\
& F(s)=\frac{K\left(s+z_{1}^{\prime}\right)\left(s+z_{2}^{\prime}\right)\left(s+z_{3}^{\prime}\right) \ldots\left(s+z_{m}^{\prime}\right)}{\left(s+p_{1}\right)\left(s+p_{2}\right)\left(s+p_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+p_{n}\right)}
\end{aligned}$$

Thus, $\mathrm{zl}^{\prime}, \mathrm{zz}^{\prime} . . . \mathrm{zn}$ are the zeroes of the function $\mathrm{F}(\mathrm{s})$.
Now, let's combine the values of $\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}), 1+\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}) \mathrm{H}(\mathrm{s})$ in the transfer function, which is given by: $\mathrm{C}(\mathrm{s}) / \mathrm{R}(\mathrm{s})=\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}) /(1+\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s}) \mathrm{H}(\mathrm{s}))$
$$\frac{C(s)}{R(s)}=\frac{\frac{K\left(s+z_{1}\right)\left(s+z_{2}\right)\left(s+z_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+z_{m}\right)}{\left(s+p_{1}\right)\left(s+p_{2}\right)\left(s+p_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+p_{n}\right)}}{1+\frac{K\left(s+z_{1}\right)\left(s+z_{2}\right)\left(s+z_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+z_{m}\right)}{\left(s+p_{1}\right)\left(s+p_{2}\right)\left(s+p_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+p_{n}\right)}}$$
$$\frac{C(s)}{R(s)}=\frac{K\left(s+z_{1}\right)\left(s+z_{2}\right)\left(s+z_{3}\right) \ldots\left(s+z_{m}\right)}{\left(s+z_{1}^{\prime}\right)\left(s+z_{2}^{\prime}\right)\left(s+z_{3}^{\prime}\right) \ldots\left(s+z_{n}^{\prime}\right)}$$
$\mathrm{zl}^{\prime}, \mathrm{z} 2^{\prime}, \mathrm{z} 3^{\prime}$, and zn ' are the poles of the above transfer function.
The Nyquist stability criterion is based on the point $-1+\mathrm{j} 0$ to determine the stability of the closed loop system. It is because the contour of the function $\mathrm{F}(\mathrm{s})$ with respect to the origin of the plane is same as the contour of the $\mathrm{F}(\mathrm{s})-1$ plane with respect to the point $-1+\mathrm{j} 0$.

The point $-1+\mathrm{j} 0$ on the axis will appear as:
