\section*{Advantages of the Nyquist plot}

The advantages of the Nyquist plot are as follows:
- It can determine the stability of the control system.
- It is better than the root locus in terms of time delay. It means that the Nyquist plot can easily handle the time delay in the system.
- It provides a way to use the bode plots.
- It can find the frequency response of the open-loop transfer function.
- It can find the number of poles present on the right side of the s-plane.
- It can also find the relative stability of the system.

\section*{Disadvantages of the Nyquist plot}

The disadvantages of the Nyquist plot are as follows:
- It uses some complex mathematical techniques.
- It cannot determine the absolute stability of the system.
- It does not provide the exact information of the number of poles present on the right side of the s-plane.

\section*{Bode plot}

It is a frequency response plot that contains two graphs, magnitude and phase. The first plot is the magnitude plot of sinusoidal transfer function versus $\log \mathrm{w}$, and the other graph represents the phase angle. It can be drawn both for the open-loop and closed-loop system. It is generally drawn for the open-loop system because it conveniently determines the stability and other related parameters.

Bode plot helps us determine the system's stability and provides us with a way to improve that stability. The standard representation of the Bode plot of the open-loop system is given by:

\section*{$20 \log |\mathbf{G}(\mathbf{j} \omega)|$}

It represents the logarithmic magnitude of the function $G(s)$ or $G(j \omega)$. Here, the base of logarithmic is 10 . The unit represents the magnitude of the logarithmic function $\mathbf{G}(\mathbf{j} \boldsymbol{\omega})$ in decibels or db . The curve is not drawn on a simple graph paper; and instead, it is drawn on the semilog paper that uses the frequency, phase angle, and magnitude for plotting. The log scale or abscissa is used for the frequency, and the linear scale or ordinate for the phase angle and magnitude.

The logarithmic function allows the various values in the forms of multiple to be added. For example,
$\log a b=\log a+\log b$

Thus, the bode plot has an advantage of converting the multiplication of magnitudes in addition. For example,

Let $G(j \omega)=K / j \omega(1+j \omega T)$

The magnitude of $G(j \omega)$ is $K /\left[\omega\left(1+\omega^{2} T^{2}\right)^{1 / 2}\right]$
The phase angle of $G(j \omega)$ is $-90-? \tan ^{-1} \omega T$

The magnitude in the form of decibels can be expressed as:
$20 \log \left[K / \omega\left(1+\omega^{2} \mathrm{~T}^{2}\right)^{1 / 2}\right]$
$=20 \log \mathrm{~K} / \omega+20 \log 1 /\left(1+\omega^{2} \mathrm{~T}^{2}\right)^{1 / 2}$
$=20 \log \mathrm{~K} / \omega-20 \log \left(1+\omega^{2} \mathrm{~T}^{2}\right)^{1 / 2}$
We have inserted the negative sign due to the inverse of the logarithmic value.
It means that $\log 1 /$ a can be written as $\log (a)^{-1}$, which is equal to $-\log \mathbf{a}$.
Thus, the above equation depicts that the magnitude when expressed in terms of db. It can easily convert the multiplicative terms to add, meaning that the individual factors of the given transfer function can be added. We will also discuss an example to draw a bode plot later in the topic.

\section*{Constant gain $K$ in Bode plot}

The constant gain is represented by K . It is also known as the system gain in case of root locus and transfer functions.

Let, $\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s})=\mathrm{K}$
$\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{s})=\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{j} \omega)=\mathrm{K}$
The angle assumed for the constant gain is 0 degrees.
In terms of decibels, we can represent the system gain as:
$\mathrm{A}=|\mathrm{G}(\mathrm{j} \omega)|=20 \log \mathrm{~K}$
If the value of K is negative, the angle thus will be 180 degrees.
At the magnitude of the $20 \log \mathrm{~K}$, the magnitude of constant gain K will be a horizontal straight line.

There are three range of K .
- K > 1
- $\mathrm{K}=1$
- $0<K<1$

When the value of K is greater than $1,20 \log \mathrm{~K}$ is positive.
When the value of K is $1,20 \log \mathrm{~K}$ is zero. It is because the value of $\log 1$ is 0 .
When the value of K is greater than 0 and less than $1,20 \log \mathrm{~K}$ is negative.

